(511, 1, '2013-01-30 03:47:00', '2013-01-30 03:47:00', '<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LU_decomposition\">LU Decomposition</a> is one of the most common methods of matrix decomposition. It results in one lower triangular matrix, L, and one upper triangular matrix, U. LU decomposition has a much simpler process than other methods of matrix decomposition, but cannot be calculated with as much accuracy as other methods, which is especially important when writing computer programs such as this one that can extend the iterations well beyond what can be done by a human.\n\nTo begin the decomposition, we first create the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_matrix\">Hilbert matrix</a>, which is the matrix that we will decompose in this problem, but the process can be performed with any desired matrix. The user is prompted to enter a dimension, and the program generates the Hilbert matrix (and each successive step in the process) based upon that dimension.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu1.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe decimal format is used to display the matrices in the terminal in a readable form, neatly organized. The next step is to calculate our vector b, given in the problem statement, which is simply a vector equal to the number of dimensions, n, with 1 in each element: {1, 1,..., 1}.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu2.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThroughout the calculation of the decomposition, we will need to use the identity matrix at various points, so we calculate it and store it into an array named I.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu3.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAfter creating the Hilbert matrix, identity matrix, and vector b, we can now start to calculate L and U. The matrix U consists of our original Hilbert matrix, row-reduced into an upper-triangular <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row_echelon_form\">row echelon form</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu4.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nNext, we want to find the L matrix. At this point, finding L is very similar to finding U, except now we will add another for loop to the method. L starts out as the first column of our original Hilbert matrix. Next we need an identity matrix to work with, so we create it with two for loops and create a temporary matrix, tempL, and set it to the identity. Next, we use the tempL by dividing the elements in the Hilbert matrix (locally called “Matrix”) and multiply it by our variable L matrix to find the end product L matrix.\n\nIn other words, to find L, we want to find the inverse of the Hilbert matrix--what matrix when multiplied by the original matrix will equal the identity matrix. Performing the same row-reducing operations that we used to find U on the identity matrix will give us the lower triangular matrix L.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu5.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAs you can see, when evaluating our error, our LU algorithm is generally accurate, maxing out at 4.108e-14 at n=19, although our error in compared to the max norm of Hx-b only stays accurate for the first 8 or 9 dimensions. To calculate X, we used the equation Lb=y to solve for y, and then used back substitution in UX=y to solve for X. Note: the larger error in maxNorm(HX-b) occurs as a result of using Python to solve for Hx-b, which can not handle such large numbers as Java can. Regardless, the overall LU decomposition was successful and accurate.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/LUchart.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-513\" alt=\"LU decomposition error\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/LUchart.png\" width=\"714\" height=\"485\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAnd when all put together:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/lu/lu6.txt\" /]\n\n&nbsp;', 'LU Decomposition', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '510-autosave', '', '', '2013-01-30 03:47:00', '2013-01-30 03:47:00', '', 510, 'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/510-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
