(514, 1, '2013-01-29 04:58:28', '2013-01-29 04:58:28', '<p>The first step in calculating our <a title=\"Householder transformation\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Householder_transformation\">Householder reflection</a> matrices is to find our a<sub>n</sub> (also notated a<sub>i</sub>) vector, which is calculated by vector X - ||c-e1||: the vector X is the first column of the Hilbert matrix, and c is the norm of vector X. We use the same method in calculating the Hilbert matrix and the vector b as used prior in LU decomposition.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders1.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>The next step is to find H(a<sub>1</sub>) which is found with the given equation:</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"add-border center\" alt=\"householder-equation-1\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-equation-1.jpg\" />\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders2.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>This will not only find H(a<sub>1</sub>), but also each subsequent H(a<sub>n</sub>) within the for loop, until we reach H(a<sub>n-1</sub>). After finding H(a<sub>n</sub>), we find H<sub>n</sub> but multiplying H<sub>n</sub> times A<sub>n-1</sub> which the first time through the loop is the Hilbert matrix.</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders3.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>After going through the loop, the program will find H<sub>n</sub>, set our starting matrix, HCopy, to that H<sub>n</sub>, and then perform the loop over again, until we have found Q and R. At the end of each loop H<sub>n-1</sub> is multiplied by H<sub>n</sub> and stored into Q. And next, we found the max norm of QR-H:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders4.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>which uses the method we created for finding the max norm of a matrix:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/matrix-operations/infinite-norm.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-error1.jpg\"><img alt=\"householder-error\" src=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/householder-error1.jpg\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<p>As you can see, when evaluating our error, our Householder algorithm is generally very accurate, maxing out at 3.379e-15 at n=19, although our error in compared to the max norm of Hx-b only stays accurate for the first 8 or 9 dimensions. To calculate X, we used the equation Q<sup>t</sup>b=y to solve for y, and then used back substitution in RX=y to solve for X. The larger error in maxNorm(HX-b) is because we used Python to solve for Hx-b which can not handle such large numbers as Java can. Regardless, our QR Householder factorization was successful and accurate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the entire piece, unbroken:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders5.txt\" /]\r\n\r\n<p>will output the following:</p>\r\n\r\n[crayon url=\"http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/wp-content/uploads/code/householders/householders-output.txt\" /]', 'QR Decomposition via Householder Reflections', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'householder-reflection-decomposition', '', '', '2018-04-24 20:24:44', '2018-04-24 20:24:44', '', 0, 'http://portfolio.jrstrauss.net/?post_type=portfolio-piece&#038;p=514', 0, 'portfolio-piece', '', 0);
